<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,726,1579]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,798,823]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Hosts.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="1895" box="[280,376,799,822]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
: 
<emphasis box="[388,489,798,823]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<taxonomicName box="[388,471,798,823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Elymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Elymus</taxonomicName>
*
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="L. Malloch (1913)" authorityName="L. Malloch" authorityYear="1913" box="[489,820,798,823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Elymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="virginicus">
<emphasis box="[489,603,799,822]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">virginicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[610,820,798,823]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref102110" refString="Malloch, J. R. (1913) A revision of the species in Agromyza Fallen, and Cerodontha Rondani. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 6 (3), 269 - 336." type="journal article">L. Malloch (1913)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation box="[833,974,798,823]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref100959" refString="Frick, K. E. (1959) Synopsis of the species of agromyzid leaf miners described from North America. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 108, 347 - 465. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.108 - 3407.347" type="journal article">Frick (1959)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation box="[1030,1202,798,823]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref103273" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1969) The Agromyzidae of Canada and Alaska. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 64, 1 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10164 fv" type="journal article">Spencer (1969)</bibRefCitation>
recorded the host of the holotype as an unspecified 
<taxonomicName box="[494,613,835,858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Agropyron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[494,613,835,858]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Agropyron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<bibRefCitation box="[668,969,834,859]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal (1986)</bibRefCitation>
stated that it was 
<taxonomicName box="[1167,1272,835,859]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Agropyron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="repens">
<emphasis box="[1167,1272,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">A. repens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,316,870,895]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Elymus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="repens">
<emphasis box="[151,316,870,895]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Elymus repens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) Gould. If this is specified on the label, it is unclear why it was omitted by both Malloch and Frick. 
<bibRefCitation box="[224,531,906,931]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref100269" refString="Boucher, S. &amp; Wheeler, T. A. (2001) Diversity of Agromyzidae (Diptera) in disjunct grasslands of the southern Yukon Territory. The Canadian Entomologist, 133, 593 - 621. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / ent 133593 - 5" type="journal article">Boucher &amp; Wheeler (2001)</bibRefCitation>
noted that other grasses likely serve as hosts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,726,1579]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,942,967]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Leaf mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[346,443,942,967]" captionStart="FIGURES 124–132" captionStartId="114.[151,264,1659,1682]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@114.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="114" captionText="FIGURES 124–132. leaf mines; 124: Cerodontha (Butomomyza) angulata (Loew) in Dichanthelium clandestinum (puparium on leaf surface at lower left); 125: C. (B.) angulata in Carex sp.; 126: C. (C.) dorsalis (Loew) in Triticosecale sp.; 127: C. (Dizygomyza) edithae spec. nov. in Iris versicolor (puparium at left); 128: C. (D.) feldmani spec. nov. in Carex flaccosperma (puparium at far left; other dark spot is a dead larva); 129: C. (D.) cf. iraeos (Robineau-Desvoidy) in Iris cristata (brown puparium to right of black frass spot); 130: C. (D.) morosa (Meigen) in Carex leptonervia (puparium at right); 131: C. (Poemyza) incisa (Meigen) in Cinna arundinacea (transmitted light, with two puparia); 132: C. (P.) inconspicua (Malloch) in Elymus virginicus (transmitted light, with two puparia)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452945/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 132</figureCitation>
) The single photographed example began with two eggs inserted near the leaf margin. The larvae at first mined apically, forming gradually widening linear mines that eventually merged. They reversed direction several times, ultimately forming a whitish blotch that occupied the full width of the leaf. It was nearly full-depth, appearing partly pale green and partly whitish on the lower surface. The black frass was mostly in small grains, initially forming two rows but later more irregularly scattered.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,726,1579]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1122,1147]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Puparium.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[343,425,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURE 22–29" captionStartId="102.[151,250,1661,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@102.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="102" captionText="FIGURE 22–29. Figure 22: Cerodontha (Butomomyza) angulata (Loew), empty puparium. Figure 23: Cerodontha (Butomomyza) sp. 1., empty puparia (left one parasitized by a braconid wasp). Figure 24: C. (Dizygomyza) edithae spec. nov., adult male. Figures 25–26: C. (D.) feldmani spec. nov.; 25: adult male; 26: empty puparium. Figure 27: C. (D.) morosa (Meigen), empty puparium. Figure 28: C. (Poemyza) incisa (Meigen), puparium. Figure 29: C. (P.) inconspicua (Malloch), puparia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452921/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation box="[441,744,1122,1147]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal (1986)</bibRefCitation>
state that the puparium is black, but it was brown to reddishbrown in all of our specimens. As illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation box="[703,845,1158,1183]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref100959" refString="Frick, K. E. (1959) Synopsis of the species of agromyzid leaf miners described from North America. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 108, 347 - 465. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.108 - 3407.347" type="journal article">Frick (1959)</bibRefCitation>
and described by Spencer &amp; Steyskal, the posterior spiracles are on widely separated projections. In the mine described above, the two puparia were already formed near the center of the mine at the time of collection. Other larvae, which were elongate and white with a faint bluegreen tinge, emerged a few days later and pupated externally. Adults were reared from both internal and external puparia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,726,1579]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1338,1363]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[361,421,1339,1363]" name="United States of America" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">USA</collectingCountry>
: CA, CO, *MO, NC, UT; 
<collectingCountry box="[728,817,1338,1363]" name="Canada" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Canada</collectingCountry>
: AB, YT (
<bibRefCitation box="[939,1240,1338,1363]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref100269" refString="Boucher, S. &amp; Wheeler, T. A. (2001) Diversity of Agromyzidae (Diptera) in disjunct grasslands of the southern Yukon Territory. The Canadian Entomologist, 133, 593 - 621. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / ent 133593 - 5" type="journal article">Boucher &amp; Wheeler 2001</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation box="[1262,1436,1338,1363]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref103273" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1969) The Agromyzidae of Canada and Alaska. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 64, 1 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10164 fv" type="journal article">Spencer (1969)</bibRefCitation>
reported other specimens from AB, BC, MB, ON, and QC, but 
<bibRefCitation box="[883,1192,1374,1399]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal (1986)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that these, along with others from 
<collectingCountry box="[422,507,1410,1435]" name="Finland" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Finland</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[567,648,1410,1435]" name="Poland" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Poland</collectingCountry>
, represent another undescribed species in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1830" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atra" subGenus="Poemyza">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Cerodontha (Poemyza) atra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex (“superspecies”).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,726,1579]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1915273405" collectingDate="1910-07-28" location="Colorado" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Colorado" typeStatus="holotype">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1482,1507]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Comments.</emphasis>
Our rearing suggests this species may be univoltine. The label for the 
<typeStatus box="[1154,1252,1482,1507]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">holotype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1325,1432,1482,1507]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Colorado</collectingRegion>
, which is apparently the only previous reared specimen, includes just one date (
<collectingDate box="[1025,1174,1518,1543]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" value="1910-07-28">
<date box="[1025,1174,1518,1543]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" value="1910-07-28">28 July 1910</date>
</collectingDate>
), which might be either the collection date or the emergence date (
<bibRefCitation box="[624,786,1554,1579]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" refId="ref102110" refString="Malloch, J. R. (1913) A revision of the species in Agromyza Fallen, and Cerodontha Rondani. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 6 (3), 269 - 336." type="journal article">Malloch 1913</bibRefCitation>
).
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
